Part II - Prosper Loan Data Insights¶

by Collins Kimotho¶

Investigation Overview¶

The overall goal of the Prosper Loan analysis was to identify and expplain the key features that affect the status of a loan. From the analysis, the following insights were made;

Firstly, it was found that loans with a higher original amount tend to have longer terms and higher interest rates, but lower risk ratings. Borrowers with higher income tend to take out larger loans, but also tend to have lower interest rates and risk ratings.

Secondly, the loan status was found to be correlated with several factors, including income range, employment status, and debt-to-income ratio. For example, current loans tend to have higher income ranges and lower debt-to-income ratios, while charged-off loans tend to have lower income ranges and higher debt-to-income ratios.

Thirdly, it was found that loan status can have an impact on the relationship between other variables. For example, the relationship between Prosper rating and loan original amount varies across loan status categories, and the relationship between income range and loan original amount differs across loan status categories as well

Dataset Overview¶

The Prosper loan dataset contains information on loans funded through the Prosper platform from November 2005 to March 2014. The dataset has 113,937 observations and 81 variables. Each observation represents a unique loan and the variables include loan characteristics such as loan amount, interest rate, loan status, borrower employment status, borrower income range, and credit ratings assigned by Prosper.

Relationship between LoanOriginalAmount, BorrowerAPR, IncomeRange, and Term¶

We can create a scatterplot to show the relationship between LoanOriginalAmount and BorrowerAPR with IncomeRange as the hue variable. The size of the dots can represent the LoanTerm, and the color can represent the ProsperRating. This visualization can help us explain how these variables are related and how they contribute to the interest rate and risk rating of a loan.

We can use this visualization to explain that borrowers with higher income tend to take out larger loans, which can be seen from the color of the dots. However, these borrowers also tend to have lower interest rates, which can be seen from the location of the dots on the y-axis. Loans with longer terms tend to have higher interest rates, as shown by the larger dots in the upper right corner. Additionally, loans with higher original amounts tend to have lower risk ratings, as shown by the lighter colors.

Debt-to-Income Ratio by Loan Status and Income Range¶

This plot shows the relationship between Debt-to-Income Ratio, Loan Status, and Income Range using boxplots. Debt-to-Income Ratio is plotted on the x-axis and Loan Status on the y-axis. Each box represents the distribution of Debt-to-Income Ratio for a particular Income Range within a Loan Status category. The height of each box represents the range of Loan Status values for each category. The blue color of the boxes represents the Income Range.

From the plot, we can observe that the Debt-to-Income Ratio tends to be higher for Loan Status categories such as Chargedoff and Defaulted, as compared to Completed loans. Additionally, we can see that the higher the Income Range, the lower the Debt-to-Income Ratio tends to be. This suggests that borrowers with higher incomes tend to have lower debt-to-income ratios.

Relationship between Prosper rating, loan amount, and loan status¶

The above visualization is a scatterplot showing the relationship between Prosper rating, loan amount, and loan status. The y-axis represents the Prosper rating, which is a measure of a borrower's creditworthiness, while the x-axis represents the loan amount. The dots on the plot represent individual loans, and they are color-coded based on their loan status.

From the plot, we can observe that borrowers with higher Prosper ratings tend to have higher loan amounts, as indicated by the general upward trend of the dots. Additionally, we can see that there are more charged-off and defaulted loans among borrowers with lower Prosper ratings.
